From: PS3 Custom Toolchain <maintainers@example.invalid>
Subject: [PATCH] gcc/system.h: skip abort() macro override on mingw hosts

When cross-building GCC with --host=x86_64-w64-mingw32, mingw-w64's
<stdlib.h> and <process.h> declare abort() inside a
`#pragma push_macro("abort") / #undef abort / void abort(void); / pop_macro`
block.  Through some include chains (notably gcc/diagnostic-color.cc's
inclusion of <windows.h> after system.h on MINGW32), the pop_macro does
not cleanly restore the macro state — and a subsequent declaration of
`abort(void)` in some Windows header expands the macro into the
declaration, producing:

  gcc/system.h: error: expected identifier before string constant
    779 | #define abort() fancy_abort (__FILE__, __LINE__, __FUNCTION__)

We work around this by suppressing the abort()-as-macro override on
mingw hosts.  Cost: an internal `abort()` call inside GCC on Windows
won't be annotated with __FILE__:__LINE__ via fancy_abort.  In practice
this only matters when debugging a panic in a Windows-hosted GCC build,
and the regular abort() still terminates the process correctly.

This is host-only behaviour: native Linux builds and target-side code
are unaffected.
---
 gcc/system.h | 2 ++
 1 file changed, 2 insertions(+)

--- a/gcc/system.h
+++ b/gcc/system.h
@@ -1,5 +1,7 @@
 extern void fancy_abort (const char *, int, const char *)
 					 ATTRIBUTE_NORETURN ATTRIBUTE_COLD;
+#ifndef __MINGW32__
 #define abort() fancy_abort (__FILE__, __LINE__, __FUNCTION__)
+#endif

 /* Use gcc_assert(EXPR) to test invariants.  */
